replace_outliers_with_mean <- function(data, columns) {
  for (col in columns) {
      Q1 <- quantile(data[[col]], 0.25, na.rm = TRUE)
      Q3 <- quantile(data[[col]], 0.75, na.rm = TRUE)
      IQR_val <- Q3 - Q1

      lower_bound <- Q1 - 1.5 * IQR_val
      upper_bound <- Q3 + 1.5 * IQR_val

      mean_val <- mean(data[[col]], na.rm = TRUE)

      data[[col]] <- ifelse(data[[col]] < lower_bound | data[[col]] > upper_bound,
                            mean_val,
                            data[[col]])
  }
  return(data)
}
df <- replace_outliers_with_mean(df, c("online_hours", "work_hours", "sleep_hours"))

No strong correlation between features in dataset so predictive analysis wont be feasible. so leaning towards hypothesis testing. We will be using t-test, anova to test some basic hypothesis.

H0: Average productivity score is equal to 6 Ha: Average productivity score is not equal to 6

t_test_productivity <- t.test(df$actual_prod_score, mu = 6)
print("T-Test Result of Actual Productivity Score")
[1] "T-Test Result of Actual Productivity Score"
print(t_test_productivity)

H0:Screen Time is equal across various Social Media platforms Ha:Screen Time is not equal across various Social Media platforms
